<br>
A Bard can commit 66% of their twisting to HP regen.  This can be kept up for an indefinite amount of time because the bard doesn't use any mana.  But would you consider it 'healing' because the bard needs to commit to doing very little else?<br>
<br>
A ranger/shaman/druid can cast a long-term healing spell that will give x hp/tick.  This has a mana cost assosciated with it, although the caster is able to regain the mana it took to cast much faster than the buff will take to wear off.<br>
<br>
A Cleric/Shaman can cast a buff that will heal many hundreds of HP over 3-4 ticks.  Is this considered regen?  The target will regain x hp/tick.  However in this case, the caster will not be able to recoup the mana cost fast enough to keep it on indefinitely.<br>
<br>
A number of classes have normal healing spells.  I don't think anyone would mistake this for regen.  But it is only a short step beyond the celestial/torpor buffs.  The efficiency of these healing spells (with the exception of CH) lags far behind.  If a player is a 'healer' then they will end up spending most of their time doing 'healing.'  Now if our definition of a healer is someone who puts a large effort into healing and sacrificing other activities to be able to heal better, wouldn't you have to call a bard twisting two regen songs a full time 'healer'?<br>
<br>
CH is the ultimate in healing efficiency.  And isn't that what regen is all about?  The ability to regain a large amount of hp over xx seconds at the lowest mana cost possible.  I would propose that CH meets that definition.  If you are losing HP at a fairly slow rate (which is what we are talking about here because that's really what people are interested in regen rates for) then the cleric will be able to gain back the mana to continue casting CH indefinitely.  And that goes back to the original characteristic of a regen spell.<br>
<br>
Ok, what is my point? I am just trying to illustrate how such an open ended question like this isn't worth trying to answer. It is SILLY to try to figure out what 'max regen' is.  Why do you need this regen in the first place? Are you trying to solo? (why a melee would care about regen) If you're soloing you are a fool to count buffs cast by other classes.  Are you a necro/shaman trying to convert HP to mana?  If you have access to a cleric and they can spare the mana for a CH (and you have decent enough gear to make it efficient) then that will be the most efficient option. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uskrilmo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Skrilmo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/28/02 3:15:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousethebackroomsecretsspoilers.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10510.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: err</span><hr size=1> was just something i was having some fun thinking about<br>
